properties.name: Barnes Court (built 1832)
properties.description: Barnes Court building (built 1832), serves as the official residence of the Governor of Himachal Pradesh. Originally the residence of the British Commander-in-Chief, it became the Raj Bhawan in 1981 after a fire destroyed the previous location, Peterhoff

properties.name: Start of Shimla Heritage Walk (West)
properties.description: This walk takes makes you go from Ridge towards Observatory hill, which is the venue of the Viceregal Lodge. Heritage route marked ends at Vice Regal Lodge (Indian Institute of Advanced Studies). Perhaps the British knew that Shimla was going to be a walkers’ town so while developing the roads they left some bench marks. Wherever you go through the town you will find some benches of cast iron installed mostly on the valley side. The walkers can sit, enjoy the view, and after some time continue their walking.

properties.name: End of Shimla Heritage Walk (West)
properties.description: Elevation: 2141 m

properties.name: Christ Church
properties.description: This is perhaps the most photographed building of Shimla and the oldest Anglican Church in North India. The cornerstone of this Church was laid on the 9th of September 1844 by Bishop Denniel Wilson – Bishop of Calcutta, but was opened to the general public on the 11th of October 1857. The clock was installed in 1860 and was overhauled in 1922. The glass windows in the Church are another attraction for a visitor. The frescoes were designed by Mr. Lockwood Kipling, father of the famous writer, Rudyard Kipling. Regrettably, during the repairs they were covered under cement plaster and for this blunder the management has no answer.

properties.name: State Library
properties.description: An excellent example of Moc Tudor of architecture in Shimla. It was originally built in 1856 and now the building is being used as a Library.

properties.name: Bandstand
properties.description: Once a bandstand, this was built by Kunwar Jeewan Das of Jabalpur. Now the upper part, known as ‘Ashiana’ is a restaurant and lower is a bar known as ‘Goofa’ - The Den. Outdoor seating of Ashiana is locals recommended place to have some snacks/beers while sunsets.

properties.name: Gaiety Theatre
properties.description: Neo Gothic structure (built in 1887) is the entertainment hub of Shimla. Almost every person who is closely connected to art in one way or other can be found here in the evening. In one a few colonial Gaieties left in the world now, this is one of the most sought after venue for theatrical activities in India.

properties.name: Townhall
properties.description: The color of this structure is just the opposite of Gaiety’s white grey. This huge building houses the offices of the Municipal Corporation. It was completed in 1907.

properties.name: General Post Office
properties.description: Next to the banks, a red colored Tudor style house, the General Post Office. That was originally called Conny Lodge and was owned by one Mr. Peterson, the manager of Shimla Bank. Go inside the building and see how it is maintained as has been declared as a Heritage Post Office.

properties.name: St. Andrew's Church
properties.description: Stairs passing up through a small gate, winds up to St Andrew’s Church. This was Shimla’s Scots Kirk once. Although the building has now been converted into an evening college for students of the town and a part of it is also used as a public library but still those who look at it take it as a church still in use.

properties.name: Constantia
properties.description: Some say that this was the first house of Shimla. It was used by the government as the Meteorological office and in 1907 it was converted into Young Women’s Christian Association. The house is made on local style of architecture called ‘Dhajji’ style.

properties.name: Bantony
properties.description: This used to be the summer house of the Maharaja of Sirmour. He had demolished the old house, where some officers of the British Indian Army lived, and constructed the present one in 1901 – 02. During First World War, this building was handed over to the Government of India. Now turned into museum.

properties.name: Telegraph Office (CTO)
properties.description: At this place there used to be a library and the house in which the library was located was called ‘Conny Cot’.

properties.name: Bentink's Castle
properties.description: built in 1930 but originally there used to be a house called ‘Bentink’s Castle’ that was built by Lord William Bentink, the Viceroy of India from July 1828 to March 1835. Later Mr. Peliti ran it as a hotel and had named it as Peliti’s Grand Hotel. A fire outbreak in the winter of 1922 destroyed the main building and all antique furniture completely. Now the present one is a hotel for the employees of the Central Government.

properties.name: Dialzeal Estate
properties.description: A marvel example of Neo Tudor architecture in Shimla. The main house, the largest amongst those around, housed the Imperial Bank before 1947. Now it has the Shimla branch of State Bank of India. In 1846, it was originally built by Captain H. B. Dalziel.

properties.name: Railway Board Building
properties.description: It is said that the whole frame of this building was prepared in England by a firm ‘Richardson and Crudass’. It was assembled here and you will notice that the entire skeleton of the building is made of cast iron and steel which is held together with nuts and bolts. This was made fire resistant as most of the British time buildings required a level of fire safety. The side rails are made of cast iron. Beautiful carvings adorn them and It’s difficult to imagine how was it done so precisely.

properties.name: Gorton Castle
properties.description: Commonly known as AG’s Office, this building was first proposed to be used as the Catholic Church. The site was originally owned by Mr. Gorton in 1840. In 1844 when he died he left Rs. 30,000 to support the Church of England. That fund was called Gorton Fund. After changing many hands, in 1890, it was purchased by Mr. James Walker of the Alliance Bank of Shimla for Rs. 80,000. He wished to present this house to the people of Shimla to be used as a hospital for Europeans, but during the Viceroy ship of Lord Rippon it was purchased by the government only for Rs. 1,20,000 together with the land. A new building was built for Rs. 11,00,000. Another site was given to Sir James Walker to build his hospital, the Walker’s Hospital.

properties.name: Vidhan Sabha - The Council Chamber
properties.description: This is the building of Vidhan Sabha or the office of the Members of the Legislature. It was built in 1925 by Sir Claude Hill and inaugurated by Lord Reading on 21st August 1925. Before this the billiards room of the Viceregal Lodge was enough for the meetings to be held as the number of members was not much and the meetings did not last for more than two hours or so. But later as the members increased, it was realized that a separate building was required to hold the meetings. So this was erected.

properties.name: Kennedy Chowk (Vidhan Sabha Gate)
properties.description: First house of Shimla was built here by Captain Charles Pratt Kennedy in 1822. Unfortunately a fire broke out whereby the first old house of the town was lost. The house is no more but the place is still named after him.

properties.name: Knockdrin
properties.description: This beautiful house stands at the bifurcation of Kennedy Chowk. The house is always manned by army guards. Initially it was named as ‘Will Hall’ and was built in 1862 by General Butler of the erstwhile Indian Army.

properties.name: Clermont
properties.description: Clermont was built in 1927 – 1928 with wood and stone plastered with mud. The rectangular windows of this huge structure, all parallel to each other, show that it must have always been a government office as was made for that purpose. At different periods this building housed offices of various departments of the government such as Imperial Service Troops, Directorate of Frontier Circle, the Director General of the Survey of India, Central Board of Revenue, the Director General of Posts and Telegraphs and Department of Labor and Industries.

properties.name: The Retreat
properties.description: It was built in 1905 for the members of the Executive Council of the Viceroy. Many Indian leaders lived in it during their visits to Shimla. Presently it houses the official residence of General Officer Commander – in - Chief (GOC–in–C).

properties.name: Sanatorium
properties.description: This building originally was built to be used as a guest house named as Carlton House. The name is still written at the outer wall of the house. Since tuberculosis was a very common disease and a number of people died of it, so a sanatorium was essentially required. This was the first sanatorium of North India which was established by the British.

properties.name: Cecil Annex
properties.description: Perhaps this is the only structure in Shimla that is made with a little touch of Georgian architecture. This is also the property of Hotel Cecil but now being used for the staff. Below the road a tunnel connects it to its main building that is Hotel Cecil.

properties.name: Peterhof
properties.description: Peterhof is now being used as a hotel run by the State Tourism Corporation but originally this house was used for the official residence of the Viceroy of India before the Viceregal Lodge was constructed in 1888.  During the Raj at least seven Viceroys and Governor Generals stayed here at different periods. The first Viceroy to move into Peterhoff was the Earl of Elgin who arrived in Shimla on 4th April 1863. The last Viceroy to live in it was Lord Dufferin who moved to the Viceregal Lodge from here in 1888.

properties.name: Armsdell
properties.description: This house is now the official residence of the Chief Justice of Himachal Pradesh. In 1924, Lady Reading used it as a hostel for British nurses.

properties.name: Sunset Cafe
properties.description: Cafe of IIAS, with great sunsets especially from March to September. It opens at 11 am.

properties.name: Verma Tea
properties.description: Popularly known as Kewal ka dhaba by locals. Budget friendly place for Tea with Bun Muska and Prantha.

properties.name: Cedar Cafe
properties.description: Opens at 11 am. Has good open place to sit and enjoy snacks while watching Sunsets.

properties.name: Himira Book Cafe
properties.description: This cafe is good pitstop for small snacks and if you wish to buy local products. Shop is initiative to support local women entrepreneurs and their products.

properties.description: Pick-up and drop by taxi is possible at this point.

properties.name: State Museum
properties.description: Shimla Museum has a very good collection of stone sculptures, antiques, miniature paintings, old coins, ancient weapons and local dresses. A steep climb of two hundred meters tests your legs but rewards you with a magnificent view of Shimla town. This house on top is called ‘Inverarm’ and now is being used as a Museum. Initially it used to be a property of General Inns and was a small mud house till 1865. Then Lord Barnes Ford lived in it and renovated it thoroughly. The hill is also known as ‘Mount Pleasant’.

properties.description: Open for all

properties.name: YMCA Traveller's Hostel
properties.description: Built in 1930s, this historic colonial era building offers a glimpse into 1930s architecture while serving as centrally located, budget friendly accommodation, featuring wooden rooms. Telephone: 0177-2652375, 2650021email: ymcashimla@yahoo.co.in

properties.name: Kali Bari Temple
properties.description: Kali Bari temple, dedicated to Goddess Kali – the Grand Black Lady, has been the venue of religion, worship, prayer and devotion for Shimlaites. Kali has been our protector for ages and has been fulfilling our wishes. As the goddess was called Shyamla, so Shimla drives its name from her. Built in 1845

properties.name: Start of Hike to Jakhoo
properties.description: A steep climb that starts from the Ridge takes you to Jakhu Hill, the highest point in Shimla. Wish to test your physical fitness ? It's said if you complete the hike in 45 min or less, then you are absolutely fit. Those who wish not to walk can take Ropeway to Jakhoo.The first record of the existence of Jakhoo temple is available in Captain Alexander Gerard’s book ‘Account of Koonawur in the Himalaya’ who traveled to this area and climbed this peak in 1817. From an altitude of 8200 feet a panoramic view of the snow crowned peaks is visible on a clear day.

properties.name: End of Hike to Jakhoo
properties.description: While returning, you can choose to backtrack or take a sharing taxi from a motor road at the left of the temple gate.

properties.name: Holy Lodge

properties.name: Rothney Castle
properties.description: Rothney Castle, originally built in 1838 by one Colonel Rothney. Mr. A. O. Hume who occupied it later he founded the Indian Congress.

properties.name: Get pictured by historic film cameras at Bindra Studio
properties.description: established in 1904 on Shimla's Mall Road, is believed to be the hill station's oldest surviving photo studio, acting as a living, vintage archive of the British Raj era. It specializes in black-and-white, sepia-toned portraits, and hand-coloured photographs, preserving the artistic style of early 20th-century photography.

Antiques at Maria
properties.description: Maria Brothers is a renowned, historic antiquarian bookstore in Lakkar Bazar, Shimla, established in 1946 by O.C. Sud. Known for rare books, antique maps, photographs, and, in one instance, a 1776 American Declaration of Independence, the shop is a treasure trove for history enthusiasts.

properties.name: British Era recipes of Trishool Bakers
properties.description: iconic, family-run bakery renowned for its old-school charm and British-era recipes. Famous for its chocolate pastries and Japanese pastries, it is often cited as a top-ten bakery in India and is a favorite of actress Preity Zinta.

properties.name: Handmade leather shoes at TaTung
properties.description: Ta-Tung & Co is a historic, family-owned Chinese shoe business on Mall Road, Shimla, established in 1947, known for handmade leather footwear. Operating for over 75 years, it is a key surviving example of the Chinese community's legacy in local commerce, alongside other legacy shops like C Fook Chong and Hopsons.

properties.name: Indian Coffee House
properties.description: Meeting place for local intellectuals, artists, and political figures, offering cheap, classic South Indian food like masala dosa and filter coffee in a nostalgic, old-world ambiance.

properties.name: Start of Lower Bazaar - Food & Photowalk
properties.description: This walk is through the area that meets every need of daily life of a Shimlaite. Lower Bazaar is connected to the Mall above, by a number of staircases. A number of lanes and stairs are there which crisscross each other and finally open to the Mall. On the lower side there are some slopes which connect this area with Cart Road. Here in verandahs or balconies are connected to each other; each roof of the building is at no distance from the other and every window has to have a curtain to avoid the world peeping in. This part of Shimla, in the entire the world, is on one of the most populated slopes. Every shop in this market is perhaps older than the next but a few have gone under massive renovation to sell modern products, mobile phones and I-pods whereas a number of others are still there who continue with the same business that was started by their ancestors.Elevation: 2192 m

properties.name: BhuttiCo Shawls
properties.description: For pure wool shawl from the largest cooperative & trusted local brand "BhuttiCo". Established on December 18, 1944, by a group of 12 progressive weavers, Bhuttico has become synonymous with high-quality Kullu shawls and other handwoven products made from Australian merino wool, pashmina, and Angora yarn.

properties.name: Thakur Bhrata
properties.description: hakur Bhrata (formerly Thakur Brothers) is a historic 94-100 year-old pickle and preserve shop in Shimla's Lower Bazar, famous for its traditional recipes. Established around 1925, it is renowned for storing pickles in century-old British battery boxes and using a traditional wooden slate (takhti) for bookkeeping.

properties.name: Mehru Halwai
properties.description: Mehru Halwai, also known as Mehar Chand, is one of Shimla's oldest and most iconic sweet shops, established in 1902. Located in the Lower Bazaar, this historic institution is renowned for its traditional desi ghee sweets, particularly milk cake, laddoos, and jalebis. Must try Jalebi Rabri.

properties.name: Historic Sabji Mandi
properties.description: In 1848, Assistant Commissioner William Edwards moved animal stables away from the Upper Bazaar to this area. By the 1880s, the Shimla municipality developed the site to house wholesalers (Arhatiyas), with Lala Puran Mull acting as a principal supplier for the British gentry, hotels, and schools. It starts early and is good for street photography

properties.name: The Tunnel
properties.description: 540 feet long tunnel here, which runs north-south was built to divert mules those were a hindrance to ‘Sahibs’ and Mem Sahibs taking a stroll on the Mall.

properties.name: Gunj Bazaar
properties.description: The narrow lane of the Lower Bazaar is lined with shops on both sides. Take the lane that dips to the left, to Gunj Bazaar, the grain market of the town lies just below the Lower Bazaar named after Mr. William Edwards as Edwards Gunj. To the right of this lane is the old halting point for mules and camels. This masala market is best for finding right frames.

properties.name: Nathu Ram Jalebi
properties.description: Nathuram Lachhman Dass in Shimla’s Lower Bazaar, established around 1900–1907, is a historic confectionery renowned for its signature doodh jalebi (hot, crispy desi ghee jalebis dipped in thick, creamy, steaming milk). Founded by Nathu Ram, a skilled halwai who migrated to Shimla, this iconic, century-old shop is a staple for both locals and tourists.

properties.name: Trishool Bakers
properties.description: Trishool Bakers, located on Mall Road in Shimla, was founded in 1959 by Shri Bhajan Dass. Renowned for its classic, old-school baked goods, it is a staple for both tourists and locals, often cited for using recipes that date back to the British Raj.
